Part I - Ford GoBike System Data¶

by Funto Adedeji¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

Quality issues identified;¶

  • start_time and end_time data types are object instead of timestamp
  • start_station_id, end_station_id data types are float istead of object and bike_id datatype of int instead of object
  • member_birth_year data type is float instead of int
  • missing vsalues in start_station_id, start_station_name, end_station_id, end_station_name, member_birth_year, member_gender
  • Irrelevant columns ('start_station_latitude', 'start_station_longitude','end_station_latitude','end_station_longitude', 'member_birth_year')

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This dataset contains 183,412 records with 16 features for Ford GoBike System in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. The 16 features include; duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender and bike_share_for_all_trip.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features include data that describes the bike riders in terms of their age, gender and their usage category(whether they are suscribers or casual users). Also data relating to the start and end of a ride, to show the period bikes are in high or low demand.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

member_birth_year (to get the age), member_gender, user_type, start_time & end_time(to get the month, weekday, hour)

Question 6: What start station is the most popular?¶

Visualisation

In [37]:
n_s_station = GoBike.start_station_name.value_counts().sum()

s_station_count = GoBike.start_station_name.value_counts().head(10)

s_station_order = GoBike.start_station_name.value_counts().head(10).index

sb.countplot(data = GoBike, y ='start_station_name', color=base_color, order = s_station_order);

# Logic to print the proportion text on the bars
for i in range (s_station_count.shape[0]):
   
    count = s_station_count[i]
    # Convert count into a percentage, and then into string
    pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/n_s_station)
    # Print the string value on the bar. 
   
    plt.text(count+1, i, pct_string, va='center')
    
from matplotlib import rcParams
# Specify the figure size in inches, for both X, and Y axes
rcParams['figure.figsize'] = 9,6

Observation: The above chart showed the top 10 start stations with 'Market St at 10th st' being the most popular.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

over 50% of the riders are suscribers. Most of the trips made by the suscribers are on working days(Mondays to Friday), especially during work resumption hours(8am-9am) and closing hours(5pm - 6pm). while customers make most of their rides in the evening and weekends.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Despite the fact that suscribers use the bike sharing sytem the most, most of them take shorter rides compared to Customers who make trips on fewer occassions but take longer rides.

weekday = ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday']
weekday_categ = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=weekday)
GoBike['start_time_weekday'] = GoBike['start_time_weekday'].astype(weekday_categ)

plt.figure(figsize = (16,8));
plt.subplot(2, 1, 1)
customers = GoBike.query('user_type == "Customer"')
cs_counts = customers.groupby(['start_time_weekday', 'start_time_hour']).size()
cs_counts = cs_counts.reset_index(name='count')
cs_counts = cs_counts.pivot(index='start_time_weekday', columns='start_time_hour', values='count')
sb.heatmap(cs_counts, cmap='Greens');
plt.title('Customer', loc='right');
plt.xlabel('Hour of Day');
plt.ylabel('Day of Week');
plt.suptitle('Hourly Usage during Weekdays for Customers and Subscribers', y=1.05, fontsize=16, fontweight='bold');

Observation: This further emphasize a high record of usage in the morning and evening for Riders (Customers & Suscribers) on weekdays (Mondays to Friday). Customers make trips on weekends.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The explorations done showed that most suscribers makes short and quick trips during rushing hours (resumption time from 8am -9am and closing time 5pm - 6pm) on weekdays, Monday through Friday. This indicate that the use is primarily for work or school runs. The riders especially the customers takes longer trips on weekends, this indicate that they make use of the bike sharing system mostly for city tour and probably leisure purpose.

It can also be seen that riders from 60years and above makes the shortest trip. Male Riders are observed to make longer trips compared to female Riders.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

There are no surprising interactions, all features explored supplement each other.

Conclusions¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system. According to the data sets there are two types of clients using the system, Subscribers and Customers. Subscribers are the constant riders and according the explorations made, they make short/quick trips especially on weekdays during rush hours (8am -9am and 5pm-6pm) which might be for work or school runs. while Customers are occassional rider who use the bike sharing system mainly on weekends and take longer trips. This can be probably for city tour or leisure.

Also most of the Riders with the highest usage in both user types are within the age of 30 and 40 years. Riders above 60 years are seen to make the shortest trip compared to riders below 60 years. And out of the few riders who make longer trips, male riders are observed to be the highest.
